Re: Mr. Bear, Mr. Bear - lyric question tranditional Jp Song
by chikara » Fri 04.08.2011 11:03 am oldwordstudy wrote:Dear Teachers - - i came across this in one of the songs i have learned (as a supplement to my study).Mr. Bear, Mr. BearLine 1 Kuma san maware migiLine 2 kuma san ryoote o tsuite Translation by the book is "put your two hands on the ground." Where is the word for "two " ? i am guessing that "te" in "ryoote" is hand/hands. ...The word "two" is not there but 両手 (りょうて) means "both hands".oldwordstudy wrote:Line 3 kuma san kata ashi ageteWhat is "kata" doing here, since i already knew that "ashi" means "leg"? ...方 (かた) meaning "way of" or "manner of". 方足 by foot? Not sure on that. oldwordstudy wrote:Line 4 kuma san sayoonaraWe Can Hear the Frog SingLine 1 Kaeru no uta ga, kikoete kuru yo"Kikoete" means "can hear." So what is the role of "kuru"? ...Kikoete is "to be heard" or "to be audible" not "can hear" the "kuru" gives the meaning "can be heard". oldwordstudy wrote:Line 2 Kwa kwa kwa kwa ....Are you sure it is kwa and not gwa? I thought the sound of frogs,croak and ribbit, in Japanese is gwa and gero?
Don't complain to me that people kick you when you're down. It's your own fault for lying there
